  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "The Bhagavad Gita, a part *of the Mahabharata*, highlights the profound relationship between Lord Krishna and Arjuna. While the Gita itself does not delve into Arjuna's previous births, other scriptures and Puranic texts provide insights into their divine bond.\n\nOne such story is found in the *Brahma Vaivarta Purana*, which describes Arjuna's previous life as **Nara**, an eternal companion of **Narayana**, who is an incarnation of Lord Vishnu. The Nara-Narayana duo represents the ideal relationship between a devotee and the divine. They are said to have performed intense penance and served as exemplars of righteousness and devotion.\n\nIn another narrative, Arjuna is believed to have been **Sage Nara** in his previous birth, who was a part of the divine pair Nara-Narayana. This explains why Arjuna and Krishna share such an intimate and unique friendship in the Mahabharata. Their bond is not just a result of their current life but a continuation of a spiritual relationship that has existed across lifetimes.\n\nAdditionally, in the *Anushasana Parva* of the Mahabharata, Bhishma mentions that Arjuna is an incarnation of **Rishi Bharadwaja**, a great sage who was devoted to Lord Vishnu. This further establishes Arjuna's spiritual lineage and his closeness to the divine.\n\nThus, Arjuna's deep friendship with Krishna is rooted in their eternal association, spanning multiple incarnations and lifetimes. This divine connection is why Krishna refers to Arjuna as his dearest friend in the Bhagavad Gita.",
